There are 9 variables, all of which are numerical. Diving into each specific variable:

sr…1 - snoring rate: ranges 45 - 100

rr - respiration rate: ranges 16 - 30

t - body temperature: ranges 85 - 99

lm - limb movement: ranges 4 - 19

bo - blood oxygen: ranges 82 - 79

rem - eye movement: ranges 60 - 105

sr…7 - sleeping hours: ranges 0 - 9

hr - heart rate: ranges 50 - 85

sl - stress level: ranges 0 - 4

I picked the database because of the straight forward use implied by its name: “Human Stress Detection in and through Sleep”. So, my intention since the very beginning was to use stress level, or ‘sl’ as the response variable and everything else as explanatory variables.

< Working with the Data Set >

Splitting the data into training and test sets (80-20)

set.seed(888)

index <- createDataPartition(stress$stressLevel, p = 0.8, list = FALSE) 
stress_train <- stress[index,]    # training set
stress_test <- stress[-index,]   # test set

Preparing the Blueprint

Fortunately, we don’t need any imputing step because we don’t have any NA values in the data set. Similarly, we also don’t have categorical variables so we don’t need to use step_integer, step_other, and step_dummy. This means that we only need to do scaling on numerical variables. While doing this, we need to use -all_outcomes() because the response variable is also numerical, or we can use all_numeric_predictors() instead of all_numeric().

set.seed(888)

stress_recipe <- recipe(stressLevel ~. , data = stress_train)   

blueprint <- stress_recipe %>%
  step_center(all_numeric(), -all_outcomes()) %>%      # center numerical features          
  step_scale(all_numeric(), -all_outcomes())       # scale numerical features   

prepare <- prep(blueprint, data = stress_train)  
  
baked_train <- bake(prepare, new_data = stress_train)   
  
baked_test <- bake(prepare, new_data = stress_test)

Implementing CV with some ML techniques

set.seed(888)

#Implement 5-fold CV repeated 5 times for each of the models.
cv_specs <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number = 5, repeats = 5)

#Linear Regression
lm_cv <- train(blueprint,
                data = stress_train, 
                method = "lm",
                trControl = cv_specs,
                metric = "RMSE")

#KNN
k_grid <- expand.grid(k = seq(1, 101, by = 5))    # for KNN

knn_cv <- train(blueprint,
                data = stress_train, 
                method = "knn",
                trControl = cv_specs,
                tuneGrid = k_grid,
                metric = "RMSE")

#LASSO
lambda_grid <- 10^seq(-3, 3, length = 100)    # for LASSO

lasso_cv <- train(blueprint,
                   data = stress_train,
                   method = "glmnet",   # for lasso
                   trControl = cv_specs,
                   tuneGrid = expand.grid(alpha = 1, lambda = lambda_grid),  # alpha = 1 implements lasso
                   metric = "RMSE")

#MARS
param_grid <- expand.grid(degree = 1:3, nprune = seq(1, 100, length.out = 10))   # for MARS

mars_cv <- train(blueprint,
                   data = stress_train,
                   method = "earth",   # for MARS
                   trControl = cv_specs,
                   tuneGrid = param_grid,  
                   metric = "RMSE")

# use tuneLength = 20 for the single regression tree

#A single regression tree
tree_cv <- train(blueprint,
                   data = stress_train,
                   method = "rpart",  
                   trControl = cv_specs,
                   tuneLength = 20,                 
                   metric = "RMSE")

#Bagged trees
bag_fit <- bagging(formula = stressLevel~., 
                   data = baked_train,
                   nbagg = 500,   
                   coob = TRUE,   
                   control = rpart.control(minsplit = 2,    
                                           cp = 0,    
                                           xval = 0))

#Random forest
param_grid_rf <- expand.grid(mtry = seq(1, 8, 1),    # for random forests
                             splitrule = "variance",
                             min.node.size = 2)

rf_cv <- train(blueprint,
               data = stress_train,
               method = "ranger",
               trControl = cv_specs,
               tuneGrid = param_grid_rf,
               metric = "RMSE")

pcr_cv <- train(blueprint,
                 data = stress_train,
                 method = "pcr",
                 trControl = cv_specs,
                 tuneLength = 20,
                 metric = "RMSE")

We know that trees require minimal feature engineering (only require missing entry imputation). So, we are creating a new blueprint with the minimal feature engineering steps, preparing this blueprint on the training data, and doing everything else similarly to what we did above.

set.seed(888)

blueprint_new <- stress_recipe 

prepare_new <- prep(blueprint_new, data = stress_train)    

baked_train_new <- bake(prepare_new, new_data = stress_train)   

baked_test_new <- bake(prepare_new, new_data = stress_test)    

#A single regression tree but with minimal feature engineering
tree_cv_min_fe <- train(blueprint_new,
                   data = stress_train,
                   method = "rpart",  
                   trControl = cv_specs,
                   tuneLength = 20,                   # considers a grid of 20 possible tuning parameter values
                   metric = "RMSE")

#Bagged trees but with minimal feature engineering
bag_fit_min_fe <- bagging(formula = stressLevel~., 
                   data = baked_train_new,
                   nbagg = 500,   
                   coob = TRUE,

                                           cp = 0,

               data = stress_train,
               method = "ranger",

# compare $k$-fold CV results for different models

# create data frame to plot results
df <- data.frame(model_number = 1:11, 
                RMSE = c(min(lm_cv$results$RMSE),  
                         min(knn_cv$results$RMSE),
                         min(lasso_cv$results$RMSE),
                         min(mars_cv$results$RMSE),
                         min(tree_cv$results$RMSE),
                         bag_fit$err,
                         min(rf_cv$results$RMSE),
                         min(pcr_cv$results$RMSE),
                         min(tree_cv_min_fe$results$RMSE),
                         bag_fit_min_fe$err,
                         min(rf_cv_min_fe$results$RMSE)),
                model =  c('lm_cv','knn_cv','lasso_cv','mars_cv','tree_cv','bag_fit','rf_cv','pcr_cv','tree_cv_min_fe','bag_fit_min_fe','rf_cv_min_fe'))

# plot results from LOOCV
ggplot(data = df, aes(x = model_number, y =  RMSE)) + geom_line() +   
  geom_point(aes(color = model)) + xlab("Model Number") + labs(color='Model')
